## Recommendations

### App Icon — primary

**Use Icon 1: the 3D codex with the mint spine.**

![icon-codex](https://i.mscdn.ai/aafdff66-9114-4d94-847b-8a77449d0598/generated-images/3e917d5c-07f5-4c15-8b2b-649077a6b11c.png?w=512)

It's the only one of the three that does double semantic duty — it reads as a *book* (this is your knowledge product) *and* the glowing spine reads as a *cursor* / *active editor line* (this is a developer tool). The other two were rejects: variant 2 (mint-line open book) had asymmetric line rendering on the right page and softened at small sizes; variant 3 (asterisk) was generic AI-tool aesthetic and didn't connect to "docs for repos."

**Use this as:** the wrapped iOS/macOS app icon, App Store assets, the in-app brand mark over 64px, the social profile picture on Twitter/GitHub.

### App Icon — favicon companion

Don't use the 3D codex below 64px. The honest analysis is that at favicon scale it collapses to "dark rectangle with bright vertical stripe" and loses the book reading. Ship a flat companion mark as inline SVG — it's the same visual idea (the codex glyph from the OG image left zone) reduced to its essential geometry, infinitely sharp at every size, theme-aware via `currentColor`:

