  <line x1="4"  y1="15" x2="9"  y2="15" stroke="#00d4a4" stroke-width="2.5"/>
  <line x1="13" y1="15" x2="18" y2="15" stroke="#00d4a4" stroke-width="2.5"/>
</svg>
```

That glyph — vertical cursor + 6 short page-lines — is your secondary mark. It's used in the OG image, in the app's nav bar, on loading screens, and as the favicon. **Reuse it everywhere; that's how the brand cements.**

### OG Image

**Don't use the AI-generated OG candidates.** Both had text rendering bugs (one wrote "codbase-bible" with a missing 'e', the other had garbled tagline copy). This is the single most-shared image of the product — typography has to be exact.

Render the OG image from the wireframe above. Two clean paths:

1. **Recommended: Satori / `@vercel/og`** — runs in an edge function at `/api/og`, returns a real PNG generated from JSX with the same Inter + JetBrains Mono fonts the app uses. The wireframe's CSS translates almost 1:1.
2. **Alternative: Playwright snapshot** — host the wireframe HTML at `/og-source.html`, run a Playwright script in CI that screenshots it at 1200×630 to `/public/og.png`. Cache-bust the URL on each release.

Either way, set the meta tags:

```html
<meta property="og:image" content="https://codebase.bible/og.png" />
<meta property="og:image:width" content="1200" />
<meta property="og:image:height" content="630" />
<meta property="og:title" content="Codebase Bible" />
<meta property="og:description" content="AI-generated technical documentation for any GitHub repository. Shipped as a pull request." />
<meta name="twitter:card" content="summary_large_image" />
```

### Why this OG composition works

The image is doing three jobs in 1.2 seconds of scroll-past attention:

- **Left zone establishes brand**: the lockup — terminal-prompt eyebrow `$ bible generate _`, the wordmark with `codebase` in white and `bible.` in mint (the period is intentional, it's an editorial confidence move per Reference 25), and a tagline that ends with "**Shipped as a pull request.**" — that's the killer bit, it's the differentiator.
- **Right zone is product proof**, not decoration. It's a mocked editor showing real-feeling output: a file tree with `auth.ts` selected, a doc page with an `## Authentication Flow` heading, real prose with inline `<code>`, and a syntax-highlighted block whose comment reads `// generated by codebase-bible · deep-dive agent`. The "PR ready" pill in the top-right of the IDE chrome closes the loop on the tagline.
- **The IDE chrome is sharp 1px mint border, square corners.** That's the spec, and it's the visual signature of the whole product.

### Implementation notes — don't overlook

- **Fonts in OG rendering**: when using `@vercel/og`, font files must be loaded from disk or fetched at runtime. Bundle Inter (700, 800) and JetBrains Mono (500, 600, 700) as `.woff` in your OG endpoint. Don't rely on Google Fonts URLs — Satori needs the binary.
- **Test in actual link previews before launch**: paste the URL into Twitter, Slack, iMessage, LinkedIn, Discord, and Hacker News (the HN preview is the smallest and most punishing). If the wordmark `codebase / bible.` collapses to mush in any preview, increase its size. I sized it at 56px which should hold down to ~600px wide previews.
- **Cache invalidation matters**: Twitter/Slack/Facebook aggressively cache OG images by URL. If you iterate, append a version query string (`?v=2`) to bust the cache. Use Twitter's [Card Validator](https://cards-dev.twitter.com/validator) and Facebook's [Sharing Debugger](https://developers.facebook.com/tools/debug/) to force re-scrapes after launch.
- **Favicon variants**: ship `favicon.svg` (the inline glyph), `apple-touch-icon.png` (180×180, use the 3D codex render), `icon-512.png` (the 3D codex), and `manifest.json` referencing both. Don't skip the SVG favicon — modern browsers prefer it and it's perfect at every DPR.
- **Background dot grid in the OG image is intentionally subtle** — `radial-gradient(rgba(255,255,255,0.025) 1px, transparent 1px)` at 24px tile. This is what gives the image atmospheric depth at the IDE-canvas level without becoming busy. If your renderer flattens it, increase the alpha to `.04`.
- **The mint accent shadow on the IDE window** (`box-shadow: 0 0 0 1px rgba(0,212,164,0.08)` plus an outer drop shadow) is what makes the product window feel grounded rather than pasted on. Don't drop it.
- **This is also your README hero image** — same asset doubles as the GitHub README banner if you publish the repo. Consistent first impressions across Twitter / GitHub / docs site.

